European inflation slipped into food
Accelerated inflation in the euro area is due first and foremost to rapid growth in the price of foodstuffs.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 countries of the euro area, recording - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Union Statistical Office based in Luxembourg.
The official forecasts only gave as probable 3 percent - announced the Bloomberg.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut off the basic interest, on the pretext that the decline, along with rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "We need to negotiate" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene on this issue at a later stage.
Inflation of 3.3 per cent, recorded in Germany, broke the twelve-year record, while in Spain it rose from 3.6 per cent to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation skyrocketed in the euro area as a result of galloping food and energy prices.
The end-of-wheat contributions increased by 88 per cent and the soy levy also reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching black gold nearly $100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will rise from 2.1 per cent today to 2.5 per cent, while by 2009 inflation will already fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will continue in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
Gallup foresees a government crisis
After a long stalemate, by the beginning of December the support of the Alliance of Young Democrats increased significantly, reaching its peak since 2002, while the Gallup never before experienced such a low level - 13 percent - in the case of socialists.
The difference in the case of safe voters of the parties - due to the greater firmness of the opposition voters - would mean support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) compared to support of one-fifth for socialists (20%).
According to the survey, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not reach the limit necessary to have any parliamentary scant: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among the sure voters there are one percent more supporters on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even in comparison to the previous low point - it has never been so high, 41 percent the proportion of those who judged the country's economic situation especially bad, while another 46 percent believe that the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
With regard to the next year, the majority of the population was experiencing a deterioration in the situation and only one tenth expected improvement.
In December, 71 per cent of those consulted, a figure higher than any previous Gallup survey, estimated that the President of the Government performed his functions poorly than well.
13 percent of respondents trust or rely heavily on Ferenc Gyurcsány, while Viktor Orbán is supported by 38 percent of respondents.
Fifty-four percent of the population doesn't trust the Head of Government at all, and 27 percent don't trust the president of the Young Democrats Alliance.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks it is possible to control the discontent experienced against the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the October riots last year, 35 percent thought it would be desirable to keep the Government and the Head of Government in power, at present this proportion is only 20 percent, while the relative majority (33%) believes that the only solution is the holding of new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the question about participation responded that they would certainly participate and another 20 percent said that they are likely to participate.
By way of comparison, in "a general election to be held this Sunday" it would surely participate only 55 percent of the population and another 15 percent believe their participation is likely. Based on the current intentions of the voters there is no doubt about the outcome of the popular consultation.
Seventy-four per cent of the population would disapprove of the payment of study fees, 79 per cent of the medical consultation service and 84 per cent of hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of voters would reject the introduction of study rights, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
The average increase in price levels of 16 percent in the hypermarkets of Budaörs' gold trading triangle was maintained, with the difference that VAT has not been increased this year.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in the commercial gold triangle of Budaörs the usual Christmas basket of the newspaper Napi, but in all hypermarkets there was a growth much higher than the thousand HUF.
As prices in food supermarkets had already been "fired" in December last year, this was not the case with a drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price far below the nine thousand HUF, today they cannot do even for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded with a minimum of 91 HUF the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10 573 HUF.
(in 2003 this basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast fillet, walnut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Bureau of Statistics, although in the Auchan we have also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
Competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was equally surprising in this shop that the price of the Coca-Cola with redeemable bottle of two liters cost less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in Napi Auchan's basket it was the most expensive, while Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, compared to last year's Christmas prices, Cora increased with 15, while Tesco and Auchan with about 18 percent of the prices listed in Napi's basket.
Comparing the values of last year's most expensive basket with that of this year's cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between last year's cheapest and most expensive basket has been 21 percent this year.
Average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so during last year's Christmas in prices the increase in VAT was felt.
It was precisely this process that destroyed trade that supermarkets were visibly unable to make a decision on the price margin to be applied for each product and to calculate the effect of the price change on consumption.
(If the trader misplans the speed of circulation of a product, he may lose a significant profit in the margin that fits the sales volume.)
The increase in the price of Napi's basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, which the most expensive was higher with 1720 HUF than the value recorded in 2006, while at the cheapest the difference was only an 844 HUF.
This year there were no such extremes, as the highest price now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased with 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic increase in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets the price of basic consumer goods grew by more than 30 percent.
(However this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some staple foods, recorded in the 12-month interval a price increase of more than 30 percent.
For example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of egg.)
According to Napi's basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product that was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, it was recorded, in the worst cases just 10 percent increase in prices.
According to all indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, being able to impose drastic price increases even on multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain in the gold trading triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our experiences, most of the consumers in the three shops visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, taking by pallets the preserved foods.
On Wednesday morning, in the three stores large queues were formed ahead of the boxes because suddenly the number of customers increased.
However, we have information that in the interior of the country sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to survey institutes because income falls below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of household appliances.
In many hospitals it is saved with disinfectants
Several thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals this year, primarily due to the misuse of antibiotics.
The hygiene conditions prevailing in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds and the overload of staff do not favour the control of infections - says the doctor-chief of the department of the National Center of Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, a MRSA contagion has been diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
One injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, and the same patient soon afterwards had to return to the hospital as a result of MRSA contagion and since then no major surgical intervention has been possible due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10 of this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the Nosocomialis Surveillance National System - said Karolina Böröcz, department doctor-chief of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections caused by multi-resistant agents has surely been recorded, and the rest are not reported.
About two thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without causing any disease.
Infections caused by S.A. (e.g. inflammation of the throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once it is applied exaggeratedly or improperly to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics, become highly antibiotic resistant bacteria and quickly contagion under inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or septicaemia in the first place in patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, in patients with weakened body, in the elderly, or in people of low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of Hospital János there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic resistant
"These patients are isolated, they are treated in rubber gloves and mask by nurses and there are antibiotics suitable for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalised patients are previously screened for MRSA presence in their body, but even so infection cannot be avoided in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital infections of MRSA in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of formation and contagion with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the sick patients who carry MRSA in their body.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most of the cases come to light when MRSA infections are already visible in the patient - said the doctor-head of the department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes strict commitments for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological conditions.
It is important to ensure that antibiotic therapy is directed, that is, microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent resistance to medicines, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent in the case of travelling patients or in basic care - Karolina Böröcz said.
Saved with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is spread from one patient to another through health personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, but in this regard, too, there are considerable shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is spread through drop transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately it can also be experienced - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals of less favorable economic situation is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability for infection.
In the view of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate preventive measures are taken, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Program Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA contagion is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so it is fought against in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
The program appears to be successful, according to data provided, MRSA infections show a trend of decline in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has as its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
Negative alcohol control of the police commander who caused a fatal accident
The official expert report has been made on the case of the fatal accident caused by the police commander of the XXII district.
It can be excluded the possibility that he was driving drunk or in a state stunned since then the resigned commander of the police of the XXII district, who on Tuesday ran over and caused the death of a passer-by - reported Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Attorney General's Office of the Capital, after having prepared the expert report on the case.
The expert report confirmed the result of the primary alcohol control which had already found that the former police commander did not consume alcohol before putting himself behind the wheel.
The then chief of the XXII district police station, on Tuesday with his private vehicle turning to Kossuth Lajos Street in the XXII district, ran over a 55-year-old man, who intended to cross the street, but not in the area designated for pedestrians.
(This last fact, that the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Transit Code are not mitigating circumstances, the driver must always give way when doubling.)
The passerby lost his life after being hospitalized.
As a result, the district police leader resigned and requested his retirement, according to the police statement, because he was greatly moved by the case.
The investigation of the case is carried out by the Budapest Public Prosecutor ' s Office.
Attila Morvai also said that the former police commander from the outset collaborated with the prosecutors responsible for the investigation.
EUR 400 million more for infrastructure
Hungarian finance minister János Veres and vice president of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed on Friday in Budapest three credit-limit agreements with a total value of 400 million euros to finance infrastructure for education, transport and the environment, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance transport and environmental protection projects in the Hungarian budget, to be implemented from the Cohesion Fund grant, of which the parties had already signed a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million, the contract they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The credit agreement of EUR 150 million is also intended to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this objective for Hungary, and the decision on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be taken later when the credit agreement is extended.
The parties signed a contract for EUR 50 million for innovations, which the budget will use mainly for the University of Debrecen's innovation and research project.
During the talks they also covered the topic of the construction of the 4th line of the Metro.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary completes the details of the Metro funding with the EU, they will revisit the issue of whether or not to modify the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this can take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990 the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest on the loans is in line with EURIBOR and the EIB offers an 8-year grace period, with no charge for keeping the credit at the disposal of the debtor.
Bulgaria, the EU’s real estate paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is admirable - the attention of the whole of Europe is directed towards that Balkan country not mentioned above.
What, where and by those who buy in the EU's even cheaper market, which will quickly be expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred objective for real estate acquisitions in Eastern Europe is without a doubt Bulgaria, with its cheap apartments of ski slopes and beach chalets.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while on the beaches of Albena, the "Costa Dorada", the "Costa del Sol", the old Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people also search for properties around Kavarna and Balchik.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, sooner or later also the central area of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will awaken the interest of real estate developers and more and more people will buy real estate in the especially cheap area of Rus.
Similarly the capital Sofia can be attractive, commercial and office spaces promise a rapid recovery of investment.
Bulgaria is on the best path to becoming one of the most attractive golf havens in Europe, thus being a top destination also during the other two seasons, in addition to summer and winter.
Therefore, cautious investors are already making their purchases, for example around Bansko.
In the opinion of analysts, those who buy real estate in Bulgaria also strive to change their life and way of life.
Most customers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot developers are also present and there are traditionally many Russian customers on the Black Sea beaches and in ski paradises.
Foreign customers can be classified into three groups - says Georgi Jankov, regional director of Re/Max in Bulgaria.
Those who intend to settle here buy new or renovated properties for a price between 50 and 100 thousand euros or old houses in bad condition between 5 and 15 thousand euros, to renew them later.
They demand good communication and access, and for them the proximity of a large city, shops and usually a local doctor is important.
The second category consists of buyers of chalets (Bulgaria in December was included among the first 10 holiday destinations of the Germans).
The third group consists of real estate investors who make their purchases in the hope of benefiting in the medium or long term.
The price of capital estates is constantly growing, as demand is increasing.
Although in the European Union Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices, in the last five years these suffered an annual increase of 21 percent
The rise in the price of real estate significantly exceeds wage growth.
Phodor and the six by hundreds Hungarians
As reported by the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, expert-level meetings will be concluded on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official inauguration, negotiations at the ministerial level on the post-2012 international climate regime will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world discuss the Bali Road Map, which provides for post-emission reduction efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, until 2012.
There are now lively discussions on this issue between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not wish to negotiate on precise figures at the moment, although it tends to agree that, compared to the situation in 1990, the emission of greenhouse gases should be reduced by 25 to 40 per cent by 2020.
Another major theme of the conference is whether industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing or unwilling to offer material and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also reached on the aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be headed by a 16-member steering board, probably within the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF) - writes the "Piac és Profit".
The Six by Hundreds of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister for the Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to retain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 compared to the 1990 level, regardless of whether or not the "post-2012 agreement" will be signed and is willing to commit itself to reducing even 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in accordance with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries signatories to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed themselves to decrease by 5.2 per cent, within this the then 15 EU Member States committed themselves to meet an 8 per cent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce by 6 percent the emission of greenhouse gases with respect to the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will comply with - says the press release of the Ministry of Environment.
Much is at stake in Bali, since the long-term international climate policy agreement will have to be signed in two years' time, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed to after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments made in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the need for which was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, an international scientific association of the UN dealing with climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would delay the reduction of emissions and could not prevent an increase of more than 2°C in the average temperature of the Earth, a fact that scientists believe would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
British Army units in a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: Special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban - reported the BBC.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled on Kandahar's general body of operations, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are already 139 recordings coming from the air force soldiers who have been charged in this way to the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "headquarters defense" and publishes videos of both actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the Community of British Nations (Commonwealth Office) and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos with recruitment targets, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present to the public the real objective of the British army's presence abroad.
This type of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional television recruitment spots - the BBC has declared defense expert Gordon Mackenzie - instead, inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the raison d'être of military actions decided by the government.
The Americans set up a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the suspiciously edited and censored recordings, amateur videos appear in the distributor, for example about the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak at most of losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fights.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in real operations have already been uploaded to the Internet from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army has only recently taken advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different way to recruit with shooting video games, which can be downloaded free of charge, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in place of the soldiers.
