In the end, failure.
The Kosovo Serbs and Albanians have ended on Wednesday morning to Baden, in Austria, a sixth and final discussion session without having been able to overcome their differences on the future status of the separatist province.
" It is regrettable that the parties have not been able to reach an agreement on the status ", said European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger, during a press conference in Vienna.
Stressing that peace in the region was " at stake " , his American counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to respect their efforts to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of negotiations.
"We do not foresee violence for now but enter a very difficult period ", he added, noting that " obvious tensions exist " .
End of mediation on 10 December
The troika mediators, regrouping the European Union, the United States and Russia, will go one last time on Monday in Serbia and Kosovo.
The future of the province populated by 90% Albanians could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and the Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko will return their relationship to the United Nations Security Council, by 10 December.
The discussions in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and final session of negotiations since the troika was charged with a new mediation by the UN last August.
Americans and Europeans consider that their mediation will end on December 10.
The Russians, who have already blocked the granting of independence in Kosovo in the Security Council, insist on pursuing negotiations beyond this deadline.
"Russia was and is committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution," said Botsane-Khartchenko.
Declaration of Unilateral Independence?
After eight years of UN administration in Kosovo, the Westerners consider independence under the supervision of the European Union to be the only viable solution.
Pristina feels prepared to proclaim it unilaterally if the Security Council does not resolve in its favour.
Belgrade insists on increased autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been found," announced the president of Kosovo's autonomous authority, Fatmir Sejdiu, at the Baden hotel where these "last chance negotiations" were held since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former commander of the Kosovo rebellion and future Prime Minister of the province, has given part of his regrets.
But he added that the plan of autonomy presented by Belgrade "belonged to a past that has led to homicides and deportations."
" Domino effect "
Serbian President Boris Tadic considered that a compromise was always feasible, warning the Albanian majority in Kosovo against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of the independence of the province.
Belgrade says it particularly fears a " domino effect " in a region still weakened by the wars of independence of the 1990s.
" For Serbia, he said, this does not mean that a compromise is impossible. "
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation had insisted that all decisions belong exclusively to the Security Council, in which its Russian ally has a right of veto.
" The Parliament of Kosovo shall have the last word "
"Only a solution within the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia ", had declared Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica.
" These negotiations have lasted two years.
They must be completed as they have begun: in the Security Council. "
To journalists, Fatmir Sedjiu had replied that " the Kosovo Parliament will have the last word on status " , adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by Albanians would be " in concert " with the Westerners.
Bush Begins Agreement Between Israelis and Palestinians · Global Voices
President George Bush announced, during the opening of his own international peace conference to Annapolis in Maryland on Tuesday, that the Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed on a joint declaration.
He pointed out that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to start negotiations immediately in view of finding a definitive regulation of the 60-year-old disputed point between their two peoples.
In the presence of both men, Bush promised that he would do everything to help them conclude a "peace treaty" by the end of 2008.
In the meantime, Palestinians must dismantle " terrorist infrastructures " and Israel must stop its colonization activities, Bush said, recalling both sides' obligations regarding the path to peace they accepted in 2003.
The head of the White House stressed that negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian Authority chaired by Abbas would attempt " to conclude a peace treaty that would resolve all outstanding issues, without exception, including central issues " .
This name covers the three main pitfalls of the disputed Israeli-Palestinian point: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem and the fate of Arab refugees expelled from their homes during the 1948 conflict.
Taking the floor after the American president, Abbas insisted that the upcoming negotiations be "global and deepened" and refer in all aspects of a regulation, citing "Jerusalem, refugees, borders, colonies, water, security, among other things."
Going up to his return in the rostrum, Olmert committed himself to what the upcoming negotiations are "direct and continuous" and to make "an effort to conclude them in the course of 2008".
Bush set at the end of 2008 the end of the implementation of his co-existing Palestinian and Israeli " vision of two States " .
Saudi Arabia revealed that it had made an effort in this direction on the part of Bush before deciding to participate in the conference.
Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis is a success for Washington, is at the beginning of a plan, endorsed by all Arab countries, which proposes to Israel peace in exchange for its withdrawal from all Arab territories occupied during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
Annapolis marks " a point of confrontation in the history of the Middle East, more particularly because it attacks the roots of the conflict and its central aspects ", says Prince Saoud in his Arab newspaper interview with Saudi capitals.
