The Scottish NHS needs to monitor the criminal records of employees outside Europe, a vigilante said.
Auditor General Robert Black's recommendation came after it was found that a foreign doctor was involved in the Glasgow airport attack in June.
Black also expressed concern that Scottish NHS has no exact idea of the amount of foreign personnel it has.
However, his report pointed out other controls that are carried out correctly through a sample of five health authorities.
The auditor general checked the number of foreign personnel hired outside the European economic area, following the attacks on Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after crashing a jeep at the gates of the airport terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who performed at the Old Bailey by video conference in October, accused in connection with the alleged car bombings in the United Kingdom.
NHS expects to conduct pre-employment checks on candidates to ensure that they meet the qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the UK.
Although Scotland's health board uses "Disclosure Scotland" to carry out criminal record checks, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside Britain.
The auditor-general's report recommends, among other measures, that boards should be guided by the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with criminal controls in many countries outside Britain.
"Although we found some of the personal records with evidence of these controls, this is not a routine review," the report says.
Black states that Scottish NHS has a high level of compliance with its own employment policies, but notes that: "Our report highlights areas that can be improved to ensure that the necessary information is available in the number of NHS foreign personnel."
The president of BMA Scotland, Dr. Peter Terry said it was "very unlikely" that pre-employment checks could identify potential NHS employees who could commit terrorist acts in the future.
"The report suggests that pre-employment checks work in NHS Scotland but it is not clear what the added value of the recommendations made is," he explained.
Scottish health authorities state that they currently have 1,161 foreign people, most of them doctors and nurses.
But the auditor general warned that the number may be higher, in part because the boards have problems identifying which employees have indefinite residence permits.
The investigation also found that the verification procedures established by the NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian were being extensively complied with.
This includes passport checks, work permit checks and qualifications checks.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing the pre-employment policy and guide for foreigners in the NHS.
